{"candidates":[{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats self-consistency only in the regime where the critic achieves high recall on wrong candidates while maintaining precision on right candidates that is bounded below by a function of base error rate and k; specifically, the harness advantage is monotonically governed by the inequality (1 - psi) * phi > psi * (1 - phi) * (k-1)/k, where phi is critic precision on flagged-wrong and psi is critic recall on actually-wrong candidates.\",\"mechanism\": \"Let B = base error rate of individual candidates. Self-consistency correctness at k=5 is approximately the probability that the correct answer is the modal answer, which increases with k and decreases with B but is non-linear due to correlated errors. Harness filtering removes candidates the critic flags as wrong. Net benefit = (correct candidates removed from wrong-majority questions that flip to right) - (correct candidates removed from right-majority questions that flip to wrong or tie). When B is very low (as in the observed data: 0.01-0.033), most majorities are already correct, so the left term is near zero and even low precision destroys value. When B is moderate (0.15-0.40), wrong majorities exist in sufficient quantity that a critic with psi >= 0.6 and phi >= 0.5 can flip enough of them. The loss condition arises when phi < 0.5: false flags outnumber true flags and erode correct majorities.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k=5 to k=15\", \"base error 0.15-0.45\", \"critic precision 0.4-0.8\", \"critic recall 0.5-0.9\", \"uncorrelated candidate errors\"], \"excludes\": [\"base error < 0.10 (ceiling effect, no wrong majorities to fix)\", \"base error > 0.6 (degenerate: majority always wrong, filtering cannot recover signal)\", \"correlated candidate errors (violates independence assumption)\", \"k < 3\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=5, base error 0.30, critic precision 0.60, critic recall 0.70, harness accuracy is not strictly greater than self-consistency by at least 0.05\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, base error 0.30, critic precision 0.35, critic recall 0.70, harness accuracy is not strictly less than self-consistency by at least 0.03 (false-flag erosion)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, base error 0.05, critic precision 0.80, critic recall 0.90, harness shows strict improvement over self-consistency > 0.02 (would contradict ceiling-attrition claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The measured critic precision-recall frontier is not stable across two independent hard-set replications within 0.05\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"The observed data is a degenerate regime: B is so low that P(wrong majority) is negligible, so harness has nothing to fix but plenty to break. The decisive experiment must operate where B is high enough that wrong majorities are common but not so high that the correct answer is absent from the pool. Correlated errors are the key confound; the experiment must measure and report them.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"c9386a6c7b3038d7ebaf9f80aed2b6bfd17ad2be03ed64556d0173f0d0085495"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"},{"role":"dependence","target":"f7c88d08c494a83766a8454ca9a977a013b3694e868b7aab5de870943489d98f"},{"role":"mention","target":"62a4b88b39115620483d82db6756e4f3c9d86261fa24593ffa7bb2ca8aba0a16"}],"typicality":0.85},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"No fixed (B, phi, psi, k) regime is sufficient to predict strict harness advantage; harness strictly beats self-consistency only when the critic's error profile is question-conditionally aligned such that it flags wrong candidates on questions where the majority is wrong (beneficial filtering) and does not flag right candidates on questions where the majority is right (harmful filtering). The advantage is determined by the conditional probability P(critic flags majority-wrong question | majority wrong) vs P(critic flags majority-right question | majority right), not by marginal precision/recall.\",\"mechanism\": \"Marginal precision and recall average over all questions, but the harness outcome depends on the joint distribution of critic flags and majority correctness at the question level. Two critics with identical marginal (phi, psi) can produce opposite harness effects: Critic A flags wrong candidates only on already-majority-wrong questions (beneficial, never harmful) while Critic B flags wrong candidates uniformly at random across question types (harmful false flags on majority-right questions cancel beneficial true flags). The observed data confirms this: even with recall=1.0 on the hard v4-pro set, precision=0.125 meant the critic flagged many correct candidates on majority-right questions, yielding net zero. The strict-advantage condition is therefore: P(flag on majority-wrong) > P(flag on majority-right) by a margin exceeding the tie-creation rate.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"any k >= 3\", \"any base error rate\", \"critics with measurable question-level flag rates\", \"both independent and correlated candidate errors\"], \"excludes\": [\"critics whose flag decisions are identical across questions (trivially uniform)\", \"k=1 (no majority to filter)\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Two critic configurations with identical marginal (phi, psi) but different question-conditional flag rates produce harness-vs-SC deltas within 0.02 of each other (would refute the question-conditional primacy claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with marginal phi=0.7, psi=0.7 at B=0.3, k=5 but uniform question-level flag rates produces harness improvement > 0.03 over SC (would refute: marginal stats are insufficient)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with marginal phi=0.5, psi=0.5 but question-conditional alignment P(flag|majority-wrong) > 0.8, P(flag|majority-right) < 0.2 does NOT produce strict harness improvement (would refute the alignment sufficiency claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"The measured question-conditional flag rate difference does not predict harness-vs-SC delta with R-squared > 0.4 across the 12 cells (would refute predictive power of alignment metric)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"This conjecture subsumes and generalizes the marginal-regime prediction. It predicts that even in a 'favorable' marginal regime, a uniform-flag critic will fail, while a question-adaptive critic with worse marginal stats can succeed. The experiment uses three critic variants to decouple marginal from conditional alignment: one question-aware critic, one question-blind critic, and one adversarial-flag critic that deliberately flags majority-right questions.\"}","refs":[{"role":"dependence","target":"c9386a6c7b3038d7ebaf9f80aed2b6bfd17ad2be03ed64556d0173f0d0085495"},{"role":"dependence","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"},{"role":"dependence","target":"495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a"}],"typicality":0.7},{"content":"{\"claim\": \"Harness filtering is fundamentally a variance-reduction strategy that strictly beats self-consistency only when the k-candidate sample exhibits a high rate of near-tie or non-unique plurality (ambiguity rate >= 25%), and the critic preferentially breaks ties toward the correct answer with probability > 0.65; in all other regimes it is neutral or harmful. The observed data (deltas of exactly 0.00) are explained by zero ambiguity rate: at B=0.01-0.033 and k=5, almost every question has a unique 4/5 or 5/0 plurality, leaving no ties for the critic to break.\",\"mechanism\": \"Self-consistency resolves ties arbitrarily (random tie-break). When the modal answer is a 2-2-1 or 3-2 split, SC is at chance on the tie. Harness filtering, by removing one or more candidates, can break a 3-2 wrong-majority into a 2-2 tie (no worse than SC) or a 2-1 correct-majority (strictly better), and can break a 2-2 tie into a 2-1 (strictly better if the survivor is correct). The strict advantage comes exclusively from tie-breaking. When there are no ties (unique 4/5 or 5/0 plurality), filtering can only destroy a correct majority or leave a wrong majority unchanged (if it removes the wrong candidate) — never improve. The loss condition is when the critic breaks ties toward the wrong answer (probability < 0.5), which happens when critic error is anti-correlated with candidate error.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k=3 to k=10\", \"base error 0.10-0.50 (where ties are common under binomial sampling)\", \"ambiguity rate (non-unique plurality) >= 0.15\", \"random tie-breaking in SC baseline\"], \"excludes\": [\"k >= 20 (ties become vanishingly rare under low B; CLT dominates)\", \"base error < 0.05 (plurality is almost always unique and correct, no ties to break)\", \"deterministic tie-breaking in SC (changes baseline)\", \"base error > 0.5 with two-answer format (plurality always wrong, no beneficial tie to break)\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=5, B=0.30, ambiguity rate >= 0.25, critic tie-break-correct probability >= 0.65, but harness does not strictly beat SC by >= 0.03 (would refute the tie-breaking sufficiency claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, B=0.30, ambiguity rate = 0 (all unique pluralities), but harness strictly beats SC by > 0.02 (would refute: ties are necessary for improvement)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, B=0.30, ambiguity rate >= 0.25, critic tie-break-correct probability <= 0.45, but harness does not show strict loss vs SC by >= 0.02 (would refute: anti-aligned tie-breaking is harmful)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"Ambiguity rate alone (without critic tie-break accuracy) predicts harness-vs-SC delta with R-squared > 0.5 across all 12 cells (would refute: tie-break accuracy is also necessary)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"This is an atypical but testable reframing: harness is not about filtering wrong answers but about breaking ties. It predicts that the marginal precision/recall regime is a red herring — what matters is the joint distribution of plurality ties and critic alignment. The experiment explicitly controls for ambiguity by selecting questions that produce ties at k=5. The key risk: if SC uses deterministic rather than random tie-breaking, the baseline changes and the tie-breaking advantage may shrink.\"}","refs":[{"role":"mention","target":"74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845"},{"role":"mention","target":"30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b"}],"typicality":0.3}]}